<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="yes"?><objects xmlns="http://www.xwiki.org"><objectSummary><link rel="http://www.xwiki.org/rel/object" href="http://opencaselist.paperlessdebate.com/xwiki/rest/wikis/opencaselist/spaces/Dartmouth/pages/Chen-Kreus%20Neg/objects/Admin.EntryClass/0"/><link rel="http://www.xwiki.org/rel/properties" href="http://opencaselist.paperlessdebate.com/xwiki/rest/wikis/opencaselist/spaces/Dartmouth/pages/Chen-Kreus%20Neg/objects/Admin.EntryClass/0/properties"/><id>opencaselist:Dartmouth.Chen-Kreus Neg:7038d3f2-9308-4bc2-9c5e-1e02a4deaf80</id><guid>7038d3f2-9308-4bc2-9c5e-1e02a4deaf80</guid><pageId>opencaselist:Dartmouth.Chen-Kreus Neg</pageId><wiki>opencaselist</wiki><space>Dartmouth</space><pageName>Chen-Kreus Neg</pageName><className>Admin.EntryClass</className><number>0</number><headline>**Rhetoric of green tech competition trades off with cooperation that is crucial to solve warming – provides cover, discourages interestsEisen** (Professor of Law, University of Richmond School of Law) **11** (JOEL B, THE NEW ENERGY GEOPOLITICS?: CHINA, RENEWABLE ENERGY, AND THE “GREENTECH RACE”, CHICAGO-KENT LAW REVIEW Vol 86:1, SSRN) Rather than creating the scorched earth of a “greentech war,” 216 both nations can benefit from collaboration that takes advantages of the respec- tive strengths of each.217 The urgency to do this is compelling. No nation has ever grown so rapidly as China is growing now, and no nation has had to address such daunting environmental challenges at the same time as it has pursued such rapid growth.218 This poses major hurdles to tackling climate change that must be surmounted by nations working together. And there are not just two nations involved, but the whole world.219 The planet is in peril if we do not all act together with concerted, targeted efforts. Ra- ther than creating a two-nation race, we should encourage China’s domestic policies and the climate change collaborations of the “BRIC” developing economies (Brazil, Russia, and India, in addition to China).220 Nationalistic rhetoric on climate change (as best embodied in the USTR investigation) will have high costs. Creating near-term tension would be especially unfortunate for the U.S.-China relationship on climate matters, which is complex, but not marked by the same animosity as Amer- ica’s relationship with the U.S.S.R. in the 1950s. The two nations have occasionally criticized each other’s progress toward reducing greenhouse gas emissions, and China is not reticent about highlighting its stronger pro- grams (greentech promotion) and downplaying weaker ones (lack of bind- ing nationwide emissions limits).221 The two nations have ongoing tensions on a whole host of sensitive topics,222 but have worked productively with each other to address climate change.223 Some note that collaboration on climate issues could have a positive impact on the entire U.S.-China dialo- gue,224 although the USTR investigation threatens that optimistic out- look.225 In the two-year period of international negotiations between the prom- ulgation of the Bali Action Plan and the December 2009 Copenhagen summit, there were numerous cooperative activities between the two na- tions. The highest level of talks took place under the auspices of the U.S.- China Strategic and Economic Dialogue.226 Discussions also took place during 2009 with other world leaders at the Pittsburgh G-20 summit227 and the Major Economies Forum on Energy and Climate.228 There was even talk during 2009 of the two nations forming a sort of “G-2” to cooperate on financial and climate matters, though that never materialized.229 The two nations have pledged several times to take mutual action to address climate change,230 and while the promises are often hortatory, the ongoing discus- sion does have important value in strengthening the bilateral relation- ship.231 Continued antagonistic rhetoric about a clean energy race will make it difficult to conduct cooperative efforts in energy and environmental mat- ters. Unlike the near-complete scientific secrecy that marked the Cold War era, advocating a strategy of competition with the Chinese undercuts these activities. 232 China and the United States are working to develop technology together. Under the China-U.S. Science and Technology Agreement, the Department of Energy has twelve ongoing initiatives with China,233 includ- ing electric vehicle234 and carbon capture and storage development initia- tives.235 The Clean Energy Ministerial Forum in July 2010, hosted by U.S. Secretary of Energy Steven Chu and attended by his Chinese counterpart and ministers from twenty-two other nations, outlined a multi-part agenda in specific areas of cooperation.236 Similar to Norway, which saw coopera- tion in fishing matters cut off by an aggrieved China after the award of a Nobel Prize to a Chinese dissident,237 Some even argue (in obvious counterpoint to the USTR investiga- tion) that China’s subsidies and other programs to promote renewables can be good for the United States’ economy. the United States could find itself shunned by China in these highly symbolic areas instead of cooperating with it. 238 The Council on Foreign Rela- tions’ Michael Levi, examining the study cited earlier in this Article that the United States retains leadership at the high value end of the solar devel- opment and manufacturing chain,239 argues that “it’s quite possible for the United States and China both to win, with China lowering the cost of rela- tively low-tech parts of the value chain, in turn growing the market for the higher-tech parts that are still handled by the United States.”240 Levi com- pares this to other situations in which China manufactures products devel- oped in the United States. Some might find that overstated, and others cite feedback loops like the one described earlier in this Article (in which Chi- nese firms eventually find their way up the value chain).241 On the other hand, warring with China can only hurt the prospects for American firms to do business in China.242 At the international level, greentech warring makes it even more diffi- cult to reach a global climate agreement. Many have chastised China for taking insufficient steps toward an agreement limiting greenhouse gas emissions. According to some accounts, China’s foot-dragging and re- fusal to adopt binding reduction targets was at least in part responsible for the failure of the Copenhagen Accord to incorporate global binding lim- its,244 although the United States shares some blame for putting forth a weak negotiating position. As China’s economy continues its rapid growth, there will be even greater demand for it to agree to limit emissions.245 Cas- tigating it for its greentech policies could foster a climate of distrust and delay further progress on a post-Kyoto agreement. For example, it would not take much for Senators who oppose international climate agreements to blame the Chinese as a reason for refusing to agree to any such agreement (a prerequisite for it to go into effect in the United States),246 as they al- ready have done once before with a resolution opposing ratification of the Kyoto Protocol.247 The rhetoric of a green energy race could give cover for this regrettable posturing. And this ideology makes environmental and economic collapse and resource wars inevitable Bristow (School of City and Regional Planning, Cardiff University) 10 (Gillian, Resilient regions: re-‘place’ing regional competitiveness, Cambridge Journal of Regions, Economy and Society 2010, 3, 153–167) In recent years, regional development strategies have been subjugated to the hegemonic discourse of competitiveness, such that the ultimate objective for all regional development policy-makers and practitioners has become the creation of economic advantage through superior productivity performance, or the attraction of new ﬁrms and labour (Bristow, 2005). A major consequence is the developing ‘ubiquitiﬁcation’ of regional development strategies (Bristow, 2005; Maskell and Malmberg, 1999). This reﬂects the status of competitiveness as a key discursive construct (Jessop, 2008) that has acquired hugely signiﬁcant rhetorical power for certain interests intent on reinforcing capitalist relations (Bristow, 2005; Fougner, 2006). Indeed, the competitiveness hegemony is such that many policies previously considered only indirectly relevant to unfettered economic growth tend to be hijacked in support of competitiveness agendas (for example Raco, 2008; also Dannestam, 2008). This paper will argue, however, that a particularly narrow discourse of ‘competitiveness’ has been constructed that has a number of negative connotations for the ‘resilience’ of regions. Resilience is deﬁned as the region’s ability to experience positive economic success that is socially inclusive, works within environmental limits and which can ride global economic punches (Ashby et al., 2009). As such, resilience clearly resonates with literatures on sustainability, localisation and diversiﬁcation, and the developing understanding of regions as intrinsically diverse entities with evolutionary and context-speciﬁc development trajectories (Hayter, 2004). In contrast, the dominant discourse of competitiveness is ‘placeless’ and increasingly associated with globalised, growth-ﬁrst and environmentally malign agendas (Hudson, 2005). However, this paper will argue that the relationships between competitiveness and resilience are more complex than might at ﬁrst appear. Using insights from the Cultural Political Economy (CPE) approach, which focuses on understanding the construction, development and spread of hegemonic policy discourses, the paper will argue that the dominant discourse of competitiveness used in regional development policy is narrowly constructed and is thus insensitive to contingencies of place and the more nuanced role of competition within economies. This leads to problems of resilience that can be partly overcome with the development of a more contextualised approach to competitiveness. The paper is now structured as follows. It begins by examining the developing understanding of resilience in the theorising and policy discourse around regional development. It then describes the CPE approach and utilises its framework to explain both how a narrow conception of competitiveness has come to dominate regional development policy and how resilience inter-plays in subtle and complex ways with competitiveness and its emerging critique. The paper then proceeds to illustrate what resilience means for regional development ﬁrstly, with reference to the Transition Towns concept, and then by developing a typology of regional strategies to show the different characteristics of policy approaches based on competitiveness and resilience. Regional resilience Resilience is rapidly emerging as an idea whose time has come in policy discourses around localities and regions, where it is developing widespread appeal owing to the peculiarly powerful combination of transformative pressures from below, and various catalytic, crisis-induced imperatives for change from above. It features strongly in policy discourses around environmental management and sustainable development (see Hudson, 2008a), but has also more recently emerged in relation to emergency and disaster planning with, for example ‘Regional Resilience Teams’ established in the English regions to support and co-ordinate civil protection activities around various emergency situations such as the threat of a swine ﬂu pandemic. The discourse of resilience is also taking hold in discussions around desirable local and regional development activities and strategies. The recent global ‘credit crunch’ and the accompanying in-crease in livelihood insecurity has highlighted the advantages of those local and regional economies that have greater ‘resilience’ by virtue of being less dependent upon globally footloose activities, hav-ing greater economic diversity, and/or having a de-termination to prioritise and effect more signiﬁcant structural change (Ashby et al, 2009; Larkin and Cooper, 2009). Indeed, resilience features particular strongly in the ‘grey’ literature spawned by thinktanks, consul-tancies and environmental interest groups around the consequences of the global recession, catastrophic climate change and the arrival of the era of peak oil for localities and regions with all its implications for the longevity of carbon-fuelled economies, cheap, long-distance transport and global trade. This popularly labelled ‘triple crunch’ (New Economics Foundation, 2008) has power-fully illuminated the potentially disastrous material consequences of the voracious growth imperative at the heart of neoliberalism and competitiveness, both in the form of resource constraints (especially food security) and in the inability of the current system to manage global ﬁnancial and ecological sustainability. In so doing, it appears to be galvinising previously disparate, fractured debates about the merits of the current system, and challenging public and political opinion to develop a new, global concern with frugality, egalitarianism and localism (see, for example Jackson, 2009; New Economics Foundation, 2008). Our alternative is to reject the Aff’s endorsement of economic competition Rejecting competition is an act of economic imagination that can create real alternatives within the existing economy White and Williams (senior lecturer of economic geography at Sheffield Hallam University; professor of public policy in the Management School at the University of Sheffield) 12 (Richard J. and Cohn C., Escaping Capitalist Hegemony: Rereading Western Economies in The Accumulation of Freedom, pg. 131-32) The American anarchist Howard Ehrlich argued, &amp;#34;We must act as if the future is today.&amp;#34; What we have hoped to demonstrate here is that non capitalist spaces are present and evident in contemporary societies. We do not need to imagine and create from scratch new economic alternatives that will successfully confront the capitalist hegemony thesis, or more properly the capitalist hegemony myth. Rather than capitalism being the all powerful, all conquering, economic juggernaut, the greater truth is that the &amp;#34;other&amp;#34; non capitalist spaces have grown in proportion relative in size to the capitalism realm. This should give many of us great comfort and hope in moving forward purposefully for, as Chomsky observed: &amp;#34;[a]lternatives have to be constructed within the existing economy, and within the minds of working people and communities.&amp;#34;&amp;#39; In this regard, the roots of the heterodox economic futures that we desire do exist in the present. Far from shutting down future economic possibilities, a more accurate reading of &amp;#34;the economic&amp;#34; (which decenters capitalism), coupled with the global crisis that capitalism finds itself in, should give us additional courage and resolve to unleash our economic imaginations, embrace the challenge of creating &amp;#34;fully engaged&amp;#34; economies. These must also take greater account of the disastrous social and environmental costs of capitalism and its inherent ethic of competition. As Kropotkin wrote: Don&amp;#39;t compete! competition is always injurious to the species, and you have plenty of resources to avoid it! Therefore combine practice mutual aid! That is the surest means for giving to each and all to the greatest safety, the best guarantee of existence and progress, bodily, intellectual, and moral .... That is what Nature teaches us; and that is what all those animals which have attained the highest position in the respective classes have done. That is also what man [ski the most primitive man has been doing; and that is why man has reached the position upon which we stand now.&amp;#34; A more detailed and considered discussion of the futures of work, however, is beyond the scope of this chapter. What we have hoped to demonstrate is that in reimagining the economic, and recognizing and valuing the non capitalist economic practices that are already here, we might spark renewed enthusiasm, optimism, insight, and critical discussion within and among anarchist communities. The ambition here is similar to that of Gibson Graham, in arguing that: The objective is not to produce a finished and coherent template that maps the economy &amp;#34;as it really is&amp;#34; and presents... a ready made &amp;#34;alternative economy.&amp;#34; Rather, our hope is to disarm and dislocate the naturalized dominance of the capitalist economy and make a space for new economic beeomings ones that we will need to work to produce. If we can recognize a diverse economy, we can begin to imagine and create diverse organizations and practices as powerful constituents of an enlivened noncapitalist policies of place.





(% class=&amp;#34;Tags&amp;#34; %)
**And this ideology makes environmental and economic collapse and resource wars inevitable**

(% class=&amp;#34;Cites&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;Author-Date&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)**Bristow**(%%)** **(School of City and Regional Planning, Cardiff University) (% class=&amp;#34;Author-Date&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)**10**

(% class=&amp;#34;Cites&amp;#34; %)
(Gillian, Resilient regions: re-‘place’ing regional competitiveness, Cambridge Journal of Regions, Economy and Society 2010, 3, 153–167)

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
In recent years, regional development strategies have been subjugated to the hegemonic discourse of competitiveness, such that the ultimate objective for all regional development policy-makers and practitioners has become the creation of economic advantage through superior productivity performance, or the attraction of new ﬁrms and labour (Bristow, 2005). A major consequence is the developing ‘ubiquitiﬁcation’ of regional development strategies (Bristow, 2005; Maskell and Malmberg, 1999). This reﬂects the status of competitiveness as a key discursive construct (Jessop, 2008) that has acquired hugely signiﬁcant rhetorical power for certain interests intent on reinforcing capitalist relations (Bristow, 2005; Fougner, 2006). Indeed, (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)the (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 12pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)competitiveness hegemony is such that many policies(%%) previously (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)considered(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) only (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 12pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)indirectly relevant to(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) unfettered econo(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 12pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)mic growth tend to be hijacked in support of competitiveness agendas(%%) (for example Raco, 2008; also Dannestam, 2008).  This paper will argue, however, (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)that a particularly narrow discourse of ‘competitiveness’ has been constructed that has a number of (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 12pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)negative connotations for (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)the(%%) ‘resilience’ of regions. Resilience is deﬁned as the region’s (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)ability to experience (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 12pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)positive economic success that is socially inclusive, works within environmental limits and(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) which (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 12pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)can ride(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) global (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 12pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)economic punches(%%) (Ashby et al., 2009). As such, resilience clearly resonates with literatures on sustainability, localisation and diversiﬁcation, and the developing understanding of regions as intrinsically diverse entities with evolutionary and context-speciﬁc development trajectories (Hayter, 2004). In contrast, (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)the dominant discourse of competitiveness is ‘placeless’ and increasingly associated with globalised, growth-ﬁrst and environmentally malign agendas(%%) (Hudson, 2005).  However, this paper will argue that the relationships between competitiveness and resilience are more complex than might at ﬁrst appear. Using insights from the Cultural Political Economy (CPE) approach, which focuses on understanding the construction, development and spread of hegemonic policy discourses, the paper will argue that the dominant discourse of competitiveness used in regional development policy is narrowly constructed and is thus insensitive to contingencies of place and the more nuanced role of competition within economies. This leads to problems of resilience that can be partly overcome with the development of a more contextualised approach to competitiveness. The paper is now structured as follows. It begins by examining the developing understanding of resilience in the theorising and policy discourse around regional development. It then describes the CPE approach and utilises its framework to explain both how a narrow conception of competitiveness has come to dominate regional development policy and how resilience inter-plays in subtle and complex ways with competitiveness and its emerging critique. The paper then proceeds to illustrate what resilience means for regional development ﬁrstly, with reference to the Transition Towns concept, and then by developing a typology of regional strategies to show the different characteristics of policy approaches based on competitiveness and resilience. Regional resilience Resilience is rapidly emerging as an idea whose time has come in policy discourses around localities and regions, where it is developing widespread appeal owing to the peculiarly powerful combination of transformative pressures from below, and various catalytic, crisis-induced imperatives for change from above. It features strongly in policy discourses around environmental management and sustainable development (see Hudson, 2008a), but has also more recently emerged in relation to emergency and disaster planning with, for example ‘Regional Resilience Teams’ established in the English regions to support and co-ordinate civil protection activities around various emergency situations such as the threat of a swine ﬂu pandemic.  The discourse of resilience is also taking hold in discussions around desirable local and regional development activities and strategies. The recent global ‘credit crunch’ and the accompanying in-crease in livelihood insecurity has highlighted the advantages of those local and regional economies that have greater ‘resilience’ by virtue of being less dependent upon globally footloose activities, hav-ing greater economic diversity, and/or having a de-termination to prioritise and effect more signiﬁcant structural change (Ashby et al, 2009; Larkin and Cooper, 2009). Indeed, (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt;background: yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)resilience features particular strongly(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (%%)in the ‘grey’ literature spawned by thinktanks, consul-tancies and environmental interest groups (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt; background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)around the consequences of the global recession(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %), (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 12pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)catastrophic climate change(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 12pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)and the arrival of(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) the era of (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 12pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)peak oil(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) for localities and regions with all its implications for the longevity of carbon-fuelled economies,(%%) cheap, long-distance transport (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)and global trade. (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 12pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)This(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) popularly labelled (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 12pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)‘triple crunch’(%%) (New Economics Foundation, 2008) (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)has(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) power-fully (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 12pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)illuminated the(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) potentially (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 12pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)disastrous material consequences of the voracious growth imperative at the heart of(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (%%)neoliberalism and(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 12pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)competitiveness(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %), both (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 12pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)in(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) the form of (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 12pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)resource constraints (especially food security) and(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) in (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 12pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)the inability of the(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) current (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 12pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)system(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 12pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)to manage global ﬁnancial and ecological sustainability(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %).(%%) In so doing, it appears to be galvinising previously disparate, fractured debates about the merits of the current system, and challenging public and political opinion to develop a new, global concern with frugality, egalitarianism and localism (see, for example Jackson, 2009; New Economics Foundation, 2008). 



(% class=&amp;#34;Tags&amp;#34; %)
Our alternative is to reject the Aff’s endorsement of economic competition

(% class=&amp;#34;Nothing&amp;#34; %)
 

(% class=&amp;#34;Tags&amp;#34; %)
**Rejecting competition is an act of economic imagination that can create real alternatives within the existing economy**

(% class=&amp;#34;Cites&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;Author-Date&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)**White and Williams**(%%) (senior lecturer of economic geography at Sheffield Hallam University; professor of public policy in the Management School at the University of Sheffield)** (% class=&amp;#34;Author-Date&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)12(%%)**

(% class=&amp;#34;Cites&amp;#34; %)
(Richard J. and Cohn C., Escaping Capitalist Hegemony: Rereading Western Economies in The Accumulation of Freedom, pg. 131-32)

(% class=&amp;#34;Cards&amp;#34; %)
The American anarchist Howard Ehrlich argued, &amp;#34;(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)We must act as if the future is today(%%).&amp;#34; What we have hoped to demonstrate here is that non‑capitalist spaces are present and evident in contemporary societies. (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)We do not need to imagine(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) and create (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 12pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)from scratch new economic alternatives(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (%%)that will successfully confront the capitalist hegemony thesis, or more properly the capitalist hegemony myth. Rather than capitalism being the all powerful, all conquering, economic juggernaut, the greater truth is that the &amp;#34;other&amp;#34; non‑capitalist spaces have grown in proportion relative in size to the capitalism realm.


(% class=&amp;#34;Cards&amp;#34; %)
This should give many of us great comfort and hope in moving forward purposefully for, as Chomsky observed: (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)&amp;#34;[a]lternatives have to be constructed within the existing economy(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %), and within the minds of working people and communities.&amp;#34;(%%)&amp;#39; In this regard, the roots of the heterodox economic futures that we desire do exist in the present. (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)Far from shutting down future(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) economic (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 12pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)possibilities, a more accurate reading of &amp;#34;the economic(% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)&amp;#34;(%%) (which decenters capitalism), coupled with the global crisis that capitalism finds itself in,(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 12pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)should give us additional courage(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) and resolve (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 12pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)to(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) unleash our economic imaginations(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 12pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %), embrace the challenge of creating &amp;#34;fully engaged&amp;#34; economies.(%%) These must also take greater account of the disastrous social and environmental costs of capitalism and its inherent ethic of competition. As Kropotkin wrote:

(% class=&amp;#34;Cards&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)**Don&amp;#39;t compete!**(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)‑competition is always injurious to the species(%%), and you have plenty of resources to avoid it! Therefore combine‑practice (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)mutual aid(%%)! That(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 12pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)is(%%) the surest means for giving to each and all to the greatest safety, (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)the(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 12pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)best guarantee of existence and progress,(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) bodily, intellectual, and moral(%%) .... That is what Nature teaches us; and that is what all those animals which have attained the highest position in the respective classes have done. That is also what man [ski‑the most primitive man‑has been doing; and that is why man has reached the position upon which we stand now.&amp;#34;

(% class=&amp;#34;Cards&amp;#34; %)
A more detailed and considered discussion of the futures of work, however, is beyond the scope of this chapter. What we have hoped to demonstrate is that in reimagining the economic, and recognizing and valuing the non‑capitalist economic practices that are already here, we might spark renewed enthusiasm, optimism, insight, and critical discussion within and among anarchist communities. The ambition here is similar to that of Gibson‑Graham, in arguing that:

(% class=&amp;#34;Cards&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)The objective is not to produce a finished and coherent template that maps the economy(%%) &amp;#34;as it really is&amp;#34; and presents... a ready made &amp;#34;alternative economy.&amp;#34; Rather, (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)our hope is to disarm and dislocate the naturalized dominance of the capitalist economy and make a space for new(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) economic beeomings‑(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 12pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)ones(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) that we will need to work to produce(%%). (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)If we can recognize a diverse economy, we can begin to(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) imagine and (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 12pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)create(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 12pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)diverse organizations(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) and practices as powerful constituents of an enlivened noncapitalist policies of place.

</headline></objectSummary><objectSummary><link rel="http://www.xwiki.org/rel/object" href="http://opencaselist.paperlessdebate.com/xwiki/rest/wikis/opencaselist/spaces/Dartmouth/pages/Chen-Kreus%20Neg/objects/Admin.EntryClass/1"/><link rel="http://www.xwiki.org/rel/properties" href="http://opencaselist.paperlessdebate.com/xwiki/rest/wikis/opencaselist/spaces/Dartmouth/pages/Chen-Kreus%20Neg/objects/Admin.EntryClass/1/properties"/><id>opencaselist:Dartmouth.Chen-Kreus Neg:b90b21d9-cfc5-4c07-8cce-3287ab8e8fb4</id><guid>b90b21d9-cfc5-4c07-8cce-3287ab8e8fb4</guid><pageId>opencaselist:Dartmouth.Chen-Kreus Neg</pageId><wiki>opencaselist</wiki><space>Dartmouth</space><pageName>Chen-Kreus Neg</pageName><className>Admin.EntryClass</className><number>1</number><headline>==== China is pursuing energy efficiency, including shutting down coal plants – but energy costs are key ====

(% class=&amp;#34;Nothing&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;Author-Date&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt; mso-fareast-font-family:~&amp;#34;ＭＳ 明朝~&amp;#34;;mso-fareast-theme-font:minor-fareast; background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)Power 12(% class=&amp;#34;Author-Date&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt;mso-fareast-font-family:~&amp;#34;ＭＳ 明朝~&amp;#34;; mso-fareast-theme-font:minor-fareast&amp;#34; %) (%%)(Dr. Thomas M. Power, University of Montana, Professor Emeritus)

(% class=&amp;#34;Nothing&amp;#34; %)
(“The Greenhouse Gas Impact of Exporting Coal from the West Coast” http:~/~/www.sightline.org/wp-content/uploads/downloads/2012/02/Coal-Power-White-Paper.pdf)

(% class=&amp;#34;CardIndented&amp;#34; %)
4. China Has Tremendous Potential to Reduce Dependence on Coal, but Coal Exports from the U.S. Will Reduce Incentives to Capture that Potential 4.1 Chinese Efforts to Improve the Energy Efficiency of the Economy38 The Chinese government and the large state-owned enterprises that both produce, distribute, and use larger amounts of energy are well aware of the burden that high and rising energy costs can impose on the overall economy and the viability and success of individual enterprises. The (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)energy policies(%%) embodied (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)in the last(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) several five-year (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)plans(%%) have(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)focused heavily on(%%) improving overall(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; %) energy (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)efficiency(%%) in order (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)to(%%) effectively(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)control energy costs(%%). Like energy planners within government as well as within autonomous enterprises around the world, (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;mso-fareast-font-family: ~&amp;#34;ＭＳ 明朝~&amp;#34;;mso-fareast-theme-font:minor-fareast;mso-bidi-font-family:Calibri; background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)Chinese energy planners do not(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; %) (%%)simply(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; %) arbitrarily “(% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)make up(% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)”(%%) their energy(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)efficiency targets(%%). Rather they look at energy costs and the costs of implementing and operating different energy-using technologies and pursue the most cost-effective measures currently available. The value of the energy (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)cost savings(%%) (along with potential environmental, health, and safety benefits) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)are(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)weighted(%%) against the cost of the efficiency improvements(%%). In that sense energy costs (including external social costs) drive the investment in efficiency. Past Chinese(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)efforts(%%) to improve(%%) the energy(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; %) efficiency(%%) of the economy(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; %) have (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)focused on(% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %):(%%)39 • Boosting the energy efficiency of coal-fired electric generation by building larger generating plants with more fuel efficient conversion of fuel into electricity, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)retrofitting older(%%) power (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)plants, (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)and shutting down small(% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %) (%%)thermal (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)plants(%%) with low thermal efficiency. These efforts reduced the coal used per kwh generated by almost a quarter between 1978 and 2008. • (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)Increasing the(%%) energy (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)efficiency of(%%) the electric (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)transmission and distribution(%%) system resulting in almost a 30 percent reduction in line losses over the same time period. • Consolidating coal mining into larger enterprises that can make use of safer and more energy- and coal-efficient technologies. • (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;mso-fareast-font-family:~&amp;#34;ＭＳ 明朝~&amp;#34;;mso-fareast-theme-font: minor-fareast;mso-bidi-font-family:Calibri;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)Shutting down outdated production lines(%%) in major energy-using industrial sectors (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;mso-fareast-font-family:~&amp;#34;ＭＳ 明朝~&amp;#34;;mso-fareast-theme-font:minor-fareast; mso-bidi-font-family:Calibri;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)including(%%), besides electricity and (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;mso-fareast-font-family: ~&amp;#34;ＭＳ 明朝~&amp;#34;;mso-fareast-theme-font:minor-fareast;mso-bidi-font-family:Calibri; background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)coal(%%), steel, cement, non-ferrous metals, paper, and coke. Steel production in China, for instance, uses two to three times as much coke per ton of steel produced than the rest of the world and releases disproportionately larger volumes of greenhouse gases as a result.40 That is one of the reasons efforts are being made to close the many older, smaller, and less efficient steel production facilities.

==== US shift away from coal multiplies exports to China tenfold ====

(% class=&amp;#34;Nothing&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;Author-Date&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt; mso-fareast-font-family:~&amp;#34;ＭＳ 明朝~&amp;#34;;mso-fareast-theme-font:minor-fareast&amp;#34; %)de Place 11(%%) (Eric de Place: Senior researcher, has investigated a wide range of research topics for Sightline, from property rights in Oregon, to regional climate policies. Before coming to Sightline, he worked for the Northwest Area Foundation developing strategies to alleviate poverty in rural communities. Sightline Institute is a not-for-profit research and communications center—a think tank—based in Seattle. Sightline’s mission is to make the Northwest a global model of sustainability—strong communities, a green economy, and a healthy environment.)

(% class=&amp;#34;Nothing&amp;#34; %)
(September 2011 Sightline Institute. “Northwest Coal Exports” http:~/~/www.sightline.org/wp-content/uploads/downloads/2012/02/coal-FAQ.pdf)

(% class=&amp;#34;CardIndented&amp;#34; %)
In recent years, (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;mso-fareast-font-family:~&amp;#34;ＭＳ 明朝~&amp;#34;;mso-fareast-theme-font:minor-fareast; mso-bidi-font-family:Calibri;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)the US has exported only a few million tons of coal(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; %) to (%%)Asia, and just a fraction of that to China.16 Even though the volume of Asia-bound coal increased during 2010 and early 2011, the two facilities proposed for (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)Washington could easily multiply(%%) total American (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)coal exports(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) to China (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)tenfold(%%).17(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; %) Coal mining (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)companies want to tap new markets as domestic utilities shift away(%%) from coal(%%). Coal power in the US is facing economic competition from cleaner fuels, and older plants can’t meet modern pollution standards without expensive upgrades. In January 2011, Chevron announced it would sell its coal mines by the end of the year because staying in the industry was no longer a good business strategy.18 Over the last two years, utilities have announced plans to close more than three dozen outdated coal plants, including Oregon’s only coal-fired electricity plant at Boardman.19 Washington’s lone coal plant will close by 2025.20 At the same time that North American prospects are dimming, however, (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; %)coal has been commanding higher prices in Asia(%%).21 Coal mining(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)companies are looking to overseas markets(%%) that lack strong pollution and health standards. Yet even exports to Asia will not save the industry. A July 2011 research report from Deutsche Bank argues that Chinese coal imports for power plants will stabilize at roughly 100 million tons per year, rather than increasing as many analysts had been expecting.22

==== US coal exports drive Chinese coal demand – domestic production can’t keep pace ====

(% class=&amp;#34;Nothing&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;Author-Date&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt; mso-fareast-font-family:~&amp;#34;ＭＳ 明朝~&amp;#34;;mso-fareast-theme-font:minor-fareast; background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)Plumer 12(%%) (Brad Plumer is a reporter focusing on energy and environmental issues. He was previously an associate editor at The New Republic.)

(% class=&amp;#34;Nothing&amp;#34; %)
 “How the U.S. could influence China’s coal habits — with exports” http:~/~/www.washingtonpost(% class=&amp;#34;Author-Date&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt;mso-fareast-font-family:~&amp;#34;ＭＳ 明朝~&amp;#34;; mso-fareast-theme-font:minor-fareast&amp;#34; %).(%%)com/blogs/ezra-klein/post/can-the-united-states-influence-chinas-coal-habits/2012/05/01/gIQAgqUpuT_blog.html

(% class=&amp;#34;CardIndented&amp;#34; %)
Still, as a recent and fascinating report (pdf) from the Carnegie Endowment explains, Chinese coal imports are likely to grow enormously in the coming years. For one, Chinese coal use has been growing at a rate of nearly 6 percent each year. And(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)China’s domestic production can’t keep(% class=&amp;#34;StyleUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %) pace, thanks to(% class=&amp;#34;StyleUnderline&amp;#34; %) railroad and (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)shipping bottlenecks(%%) from mining centers in Shanxi, Shaanxi and Inner Mongolia provinces. What’s more, the Carnegie report notes, (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;mso-bidi-font-family:Calibri;background: yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)the(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; %) Chinese (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)government is becoming(%%) increasingly (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;mso-bidi-font-family:Calibri;background: yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)sensitive to(%%) the ecological (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;mso-bidi-font-family:Calibri;background: yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)damage wrought by domestic coal mining(%%) — as well as to the growing number of protests over unsafe mining conditions. According to official statistics, 6,027 Chinese miners died in 2004, though the real number is probably higher. There are real costs to ramping up production in China. As a result, (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;mso-bidi-font-family: Calibri;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)China will(%%) likely(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)try to import a growing share of its coal(%%) in the coming years. Much of that will likely come from Indonesia and Australia, since China’s import infrastructure is geared toward those two regions. But many(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; %) analysts expect the U(%%)nited (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; %)S(%%)tates (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; %)to play an increasingly crucial role (%%)in coming years. ((% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; %)To date, the U.S. has been supplying China with just small amounts(%%) of coking coal, which is used for iron and steel production and which is less readily available in China.) And (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;mso-bidi-font-family: Calibri;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)if American coal starts pouring into China, that(% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; %)will(%%) help (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;mso-bidi-font-family:Calibri; background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)keep prices down(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; %). If that happens, (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)Chinese power plants(%%) and factories (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;mso-bidi-font-family:Calibri;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)will burn(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; %) (%%)even (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;mso-bidi-font-family:Calibri;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)more coal and use the stuff less efficiently(%%) than they otherwise would. Grist’s David Roberts points to a recent paper (pdf) by Thomas M. Power, a former economics professor at the University of Montana, finding that Chinese coal habits are highly sensitive to prices: Opening the Asian import market to dramatic increases in U.S. coal will drive down coal prices in that market. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)Several empirical studies(% class=&amp;#34;StyleUnderline&amp;#34; %) of(%%) energy in (% class=&amp;#34;StyleUnderline&amp;#34; %)China(%%) have (% class=&amp;#34;StyleUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)demonstrated that coal(% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; %)consumption(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)is highly sensitive to cost(%%).(%%) One recent study found that a 10 percent reduction in coal cost would result in a 12 percent increase in coal consumption. Another found that over half of the gain in China’s “energy intensity” improvement during the 1990s was a response to prices. In other words, coal exports will mean cheaper coal in Asia, and cheaper coal means more coal will be burned than would otherwise be the case

==== Cheap coal leads to runaway warming – it locks in Chinese coal dependence for the next half century ====

(% class=&amp;#34;Nothing&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;Author-Date&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt; mso-fareast-font-family:~&amp;#34;ＭＳ 明朝~&amp;#34;;mso-fareast-theme-font:minor-fareast; background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)Power 12(% class=&amp;#34;Author-Date&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:12.0pt;mso-fareast-font-family:~&amp;#34;ＭＳ 明朝~&amp;#34;; mso-fareast-theme-font:minor-fareast&amp;#34; %) (%%)(Dr. Thomas M. Power, University of Montana, Professor Emeritus)

(% class=&amp;#34;Nothing&amp;#34; %)
(“The Greenhouse Gas Impact of Exporting Coal from the West Coast” http:~/~/www.sightline.org/wp-content/uploads/downloads/2012/02/Coal-Power-White-Paper.pdf)

(% class=&amp;#34;CardIndented&amp;#34; %)
Although the economic life of coal-fired generators is often given as 30 or 35 years, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)a(%%) permitted, operating, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)electric generator is kept on line(%%) a lot longer than that, as long as (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)50 or more years through(%%) ongoing (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)renovations(%%) and upgrades. Because of that long operating life, the impact of the (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)lower Asian coal prices(%%) and costs triggered by PRB coal competing with other coal sources cannot be measured by the number of tons of coal exported each year. Those lower coal costs(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)will lead to commitments to more coal(%%) being burned (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;mso-fareast-font-family:~&amp;#34;ＭＳ 明朝~&amp;#34;;mso-fareast-theme-font:minor-fareast; mso-bidi-font-family:Calibri;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)for a half-century(%%) going forward. That time-frame is very important.(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)During(%%) exactly (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)this time frame,(%%) the next half-century, the (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;mso-fareast-font-family: ~&amp;#34;ＭＳ 明朝~&amp;#34;;mso-fareast-theme-font:minor-fareast;mso-bidi-font-family:Calibri; background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)nations(%%) of the world (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;mso-fareast-font-family:~&amp;#34;ＭＳ 明朝~&amp;#34;;mso-fareast-theme-font: minor-fareast;mso-bidi-font-family:Calibri;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)will have to get(%%) their greenhouse gas(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)emission stabilized(%%) and then reduced(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)or(%%) the concentrations of (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)greenhouse(% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;mso-fareast-font-family:~&amp;#34;ＭＳ 明朝~&amp;#34;;mso-fareast-theme-font: minor-fareast;mso-bidi-font-family:Calibri;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)gases(%%) in the atmosphere (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;mso-fareast-font-family:~&amp;#34;ＭＳ 明朝~&amp;#34;;mso-fareast-theme-font:minor-fareast; mso-bidi-font-family:Calibri;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)may pass a point that will make it(%%) very (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;mso-fareast-font-family:~&amp;#34;ＭＳ 明朝~&amp;#34;;mso-fareast-theme-font:minor-fareast; mso-bidi-font-family:Calibri;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)difficult to avoid massive(%%), ongoing, negative (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;mso-fareast-font-family:~&amp;#34;ＭＳ 明朝~&amp;#34;;mso-fareast-theme-font:minor-fareast; mso-bidi-font-family:Calibri;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)climate impacts(%%). Taking actions now that encourage fifty-years of more coal consumption around the world is not a minor matter. Put more positively, (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;mso-fareast-font-family:~&amp;#34;ＭＳ 明朝~&amp;#34;;mso-fareast-theme-font: minor-fareast;mso-bidi-font-family:Calibri;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)allowing coal prices to rise(%%) (and more closely approximate their full cost, including “external” costs) (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;mso-fareast-font-family:~&amp;#34;ＭＳ 明朝~&amp;#34;;mso-fareast-theme-font: minor-fareast;mso-bidi-font-family:Calibri;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)will encourage(%%) extensive investments in improving the efficiency with which coal is used and(% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)the shift to cleaner(%%) sources of (% class=&amp;#34;DebateUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;mso-fareast-font-family:~&amp;#34;ＭＳ 明朝~&amp;#34;;mso-fareast-theme-font: minor-fareast;mso-bidi-font-family:Calibri;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)energy(%%). This will lead to long-term reductions in greenhouse gas emissions that will also last well into the next half-century.57

